Hey everyone! 👋

I recently had the opportunity to interview with AMLA Commerce, and one of the intriguing coding questions thrown my way was about counting the frequency of each character in a string. 🤔💻

It was a fascinating challenge that required a combination of logic, data manipulation, and a keen eye for detail. I dove headfirst into the problem, exploring different approaches and refining my code to ensure efficiency.

Here's a snippet of what I came up with:

```#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_map>

void countCharacterFrequency(const std::string& s) {
    // Initialize an unordered_map to store character frequencies
    std::unordered_map<char, int> charFrequency;

    // Iterate through each character in the string
    for (char ch : s) {
        // Check if the character is already in the unordered_map
        if (charFrequency.find(ch) != charFrequency.end()) {
            // Increment the count if the character is already present
            charFrequency[ch]++;
        } else {
            // Add the character to the unordered_map with a count of 1 if it's not present
            charFrequency[ch] = 1;
        }
    }

    // Print or process the result as needed
    std::cout << "Character frequencies:" << std::endl;
    for (const auto& pair : charFrequency) {
        std::cout << pair.first << ": " << pair.second << std::endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    // Example usage
    std::string inputString = "amla-commerce";
    countCharacterFrequency(inputString);

    return 0;
}
```

This snippet utilizes a Map to keep track of the frequency of each character in the given string. It's a versatile and efficient solution that can be adapted for various scenarios.

